						               													<description>In this game we will have to use biological clues, such as the type of teeth and the toxicity of the snakes, to stack the cards one on top of the other until we only have one in hand.&amp;#10;In this way we will go in each game learning about how to identify the different species present in the Colombian Amazonia.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;CONTENTS&amp;#10;The game consists of 60 cards: 13 cards for each family (Boidae, Colubridae, Elapidae, Viperidae), 4 jokers and 4 instructions. Each card has the following information: family name, scientific name of the species and common name, the relevant characteristic in the photo that allows it to be recognized as dangerous (red triangle), and harmless (green triangle) and the icon of the type of dentition. Two cards from each family are punishment cards. There are 4 jokers that represent the 4 types of dentition: aglyphous, solenoglyphous, opisthoglyphous and proteroglyphous; each informs about the family or families that have it, its icon, the characteristics of the dentition in text and in a drawing, and if it is associated with dangerous (red triangle) or harmless (green triangle) snakes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
